{"/service/ndnp/arhi/batch_arhi_igglybuff_ver01/data/sn89051213/00414213066/1907112801/0670.xml":{"full_text":"WILL MENA SCHOOL\nDISTRICT GET\n1 HENDRIX ACADEMY?\ni\nCompromise Suggested by Inter\nested Parties to Put an End\nto Litigation.\n\nMANY INTERESTED HERE\n\nNo Action Can Be Taken Without the\nApproval of the 'M. E. Church,\nSouth, Conference, Which\nMeets November 27.\nm\nI\n\nSteps have been taken recently\nto bring order out of chaos in\nrelation to the Mena Hendrix\nf Academy property to tbo end\nthat it serve some good purpose\nto the city of Mena and at t*he\nsame time render justice to all\ninterests involved,\nJ Following are the terms of a\nj Compromise that has been sug\ngested, which must come before\nthe conference of the M. E.\nchurch, South, to be convened at\nif Little Rock on November 27, for\nits acceptance or rejection:\ns Arkansas Townsite Company, J. S.\nKelly et at, Plaintiffs,\nvs.\n3 Hendrix College, W. W Martin, Trust\ns' ee, et al, Defendants. R. R. Moore:\nIntervenor.\u2014In Polk Chancery Court.\n\nAt a conference in the city of Little\nRock between R. M. Quigley, a citizen\nof Mena, Ark., J. C. Clark as attorney\ni for Hendrix College, J. E. Wootton as\nlessee of the Mena Academy, it was\nf suggested that the pending litigation\nbe settled on the following basis:\nFirst. Hendrix College is to deed\nthe Mena Acadeny to the Public School\nI district of Mena, Ark.\nSecond. Hendrix College is to deed\na property known as the Commercial\nhotel to J. E. Wootton.\nThird. The Arkansas Townsite Com\npany is to join in the deed of the\nAcademy property to the Mena Public\nSchool.\nFourth. The public school district of\nMena, Ark., shall pay to J. E. Wootton\nthe sum of $600 by way of pay for\nbetterment placed by him on the Mena\nAcademy.\nFifth. The public school district of\nMena shall pay to Hendrix College the\nsum of one thousand ($1,000) dollars by\nI way of reimbursement to said college\nfor expenses incurred by it in attempt\ning to operate Mena Academy, and\nincidental costs of this suit.\nIf the above suggestions are approved\nby all parties to the litigation and by\nthe Mena Chancery Court, same shall\nthen become effective. We recommend\nthe adoption of the above mentioned\nmethod of settling said litigation.\nJ. E. Wootton,\nJ. C. Clark,\nR. M. Quigley.\nWhen the Hendrix College\nceased to conduct a school in the\nMena Hendrix Acadeny here, as\nprovided under the grant which\ngave it control of the property,\nthere arose a good deal of contro\nversy as to what should become\nof the buildings and site, valued\nat about $10,000, the land of\nwhich was given by the Arkansas\nTownsite Company and the build\nings furnished by the citizens of\nMena.\nThis was brought to a focus by\nthe action of the college author\nities in undertaking to transfer\nthe property to J. E Wootton by\nway of a 99 year lease in exchange\nfor the Commerical Hotel proper\nty, and resulted in a suit being\nbrought in the chancery court by\nthe Arkansas Townsite Company\nand citizens of Meua against\nHendrix college and others to set\naside the lease on the grounds\nthat under the conditions Hen\ndrix college had no legal rights\nin the property except to use for\nan academy as provided origin\nally.\nThp rniirt rnlp*! that th.\u00bb <>U\nyear lease was in effect a sale ot\nI the property, and declared it\nt void, at the same time placing it\nunder the control of the M. E\nchurch, South, and naming W.\nE. Anderson, G. L. Lochridge\nand Dr. K. D. C. Dodd, now\nI deceased, as a board to represent\nj the church and uave charge of\nthe academy.\nThis board decided to allow\nI Prof. Wootton to remain in pos\nsession of the property pending\nthe settlement of the litigation,\n!but he found it impractical to\ncontinue his school and it was\nclosed about three months ago,\nl the professor going to the Hunt*\nington (Tenn.) Business College,\nMrs. Wootton and family remain\n1 ing in the dormitory building.\nInquiries made by The Star\ndevelop that citizens generally\nwould be much pleased could such\nan agreement be reached. This\nI is particular!? true of those who\nI understand the urgent need of a\nhigh school, which such a dispo\nsition of the property might make\nsoon practical.\nThe church, however, will\nprobably resist any plau which\ngives it no consideration for its\ninterest, especially considering\nthe favorable decision given it by\ntiie chancery court.\nIn this tbree-cornered contro\nversy Norwood Alley represent\nid the city, J. C. Clark lfendri>\nCollege and Prof. Wootton. and\n.Judge J. M. Carter the Metho\ndist conference.\nFor Sale\u2014Choice Strawbern\n(plants for sale by Henry Light\ncap, Eagleton, Ark. 44w(\nOKLAHOMA MAY HELP.\nRepresentative-Elect Jones lfrul Intro\nduce Bill to Put $5,009,OOu in\nCirculation.\nGuthrie, Ok,> Nov. 22.\u2014C. G.\nJones, Republican representative\nelect from Oklahoma City, stated\nyesterday that be would intro\nduce a bill in the legislature\nshortly after the convening ot\nthat body, to provide for State\nTreasurer Menefceto lend money,\npurchase good and sufficient\nsecurities and issue warrants up\non the $5,000,000 Indian Territory\nschool fund now on ileposite in\nWashington.\nThis plan he believes, will re\nsult in $5,000,000 being placed in\ncirculation in the state.\n\u201cThe primary cause of the pro\nposed action is to relieve the\npresent financial embarrassment,\nand for that reason the amouuts\nto be loaned will be limited,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Jones \u201cOnly the inter\nest on the $5,000,000 can be used\nfor school purposes. The princi\npal will remain intact.\u201d\nThis fund was donated to the\nstate by the enabling act in lieu\nof no school lands in Indian\nTerritory.\nSCALDED UNDER HIS ENGINE.\nCotton Belt Fireman Meets Death When\nDrivers Jump Rails.\nPine Bluff, Nov. 21.\u2014The body\nof John ii. Williams, a former\nfireman on the Cotton Belt rail\nroad, who was killed Tuesday at\nNew Louisville in a wreck has\nbeen brought to this city and will\nbe buried Sunday morning,\nWilliams resided here. His\ndeath was the result of a peculiar\naccident. He was firing on an\nengine on the Cotton Belt Tues\nday, when the engine broke down\nnear New Louisville. The en\ngine was pulling a freight, and\nanother engine had to be brought\nto the scene to pull the disabled\none on to a sidetrack in order to\nlet a passengerpass by. Williams\nwas alone on the engine while it\nwas being pushed on to the side\ntrack, together with the rest of\nthe train, when one of the engine\nwheels slipped off the track. The\nengine was overturned. William\nwas hurled against the top of the\ncab and knocked unconscious,\nand when found was lying in\nboiling hot steam and water,\nwhich had escaped from the over\nturned boiler. He was cooked to\ndeath when found.\nNEW WALK AT DEPOT.\nThe Kansas City Southern Will Replace\nOld Ones With Concrete at Once.\nAmong the improvements to be\nmade by the Kansas City Southern\nat this place will be the replacing\nof a concrete walkway to take the\nplace of the old plank one which has\nbeen in use since the building of the\npassenger depot about ten years ago.\nThe contract for this work has\nbeen awarded to E. W. Miller of\nJoplin, Mo., who is now in the city,\nand who on Monday morning put a\nlarge force of men at work on the\njob. This new walkway will be 290\nfeet in length and in width will be\n15 and 18 feet. The passage way\nbetween the depot and eating house\nwill also be put down in cement.\nM. P. Pringle, building inspector of\nthe K. C. S., is also here and he will\nremain to see that the work is done\naccording to the plans and specifi\ncations.\nSo far there has been no re\ntrenchment on the Kansas City\nSouthern and officials say there is\nnot likely to be. The construction\nforces which have been maintained\nin so large a way the past summer,\nI in m iking extensive permanent im\nI provements on the line of road, are\nstill working full time and full\nforce. \u2018\u2018Not a man laid off and not\nlikely to be,\u201d is the report of the\nofficers.\nTHEN A FOOTPAD GOT IT.\nPine Bluff Man Drew Money From\nBank and Is Now Sorry.\nPine Bluff, Nov. 21.\u2014George\nMayback, a well known resident\nof this city, was one of tho*e who\nbecame scared when a serious\nfinancial panic threatened a week\nor so ago and who, as the result\nof his fright, drew out $(>0 which\nhe had deposited in a local bank.\nHe is now bemoaning hasty\naction, as he was held up last\nnight on his road home and the\nentire amount was taken away\nfrom him by the hold up artist.\nAfter drawing his money out of\nthe bank Mayback carried it\nabout with him. He experienced\nno trouble until last night, when\nen route home, he was accosted in\na dark and lonely spot by a\nstranger wearing a mask and\ncarrying a dangerous looking\nrevolver. He was told to \u201cfork\nup,\u201d and he did. As a result he\nhis sworn a solemn vow never to\nbecome hasty when a financial\npanic threatens.\nALWAYS WAS SICK.\nWhen a man \u00abay\u00bb he always was sick\u2014\ntrouble*! with a cough that lasted all winter\n\u2014what would .vou think If he should say\u2014he\nnever was sick since using Hallard's More\nhound Syrup. Such a man exists.\nMr. J. c. Clark. Denver, Colorado, writes:\n\u201cKor years 1 was troubled with a severe cough\nthat would last all winter. This oou gh left\nme In a miserable concilium. I tried Hal lard's\nHorehound Syrup and have not had a sick\nday since. That's what It did for me.\" Sold\n1 by Jackson Drug Co.\nDAVIS AND CLARKE\nTO WASHINGTON\nThe Arkansas Senators Will Leave for\nthe Capitol City Monday\u2014No Plans\nAnnounced of Interest to\nArkansas.\nLittle Rock, Nov. 22 \u2014Senator\nJeff Davis will leave next Mon\nday night for Washington, to at\ntend the long session of the\nUnited States senate, as one of\nthe two representatives of Arkan\nsas in that body. Senator J. I\u2019.\nClarke, the other representative\nof the state in the senate, will\nleave between now and Monday\nnight for the same place. Both\nwill be gone about seven months,\nas a seven months\u2019 session of the\nsenate will be held. During that\ntime they will probably return to\nLittle Rock for a visit or two.\nSenator Davis stated yesterday\nthat he would likely return in\nthe spring for a short rest and\nvisit.\nBoth senators go to Washing\nton alone, with the exception of\ntheir secretaries. Senator Davis\nstated yesterday that h;s wife\nand family would remain here\nfor the present, but that later on\nhe expected to have Mrs. Davis\nII m A t inn Anil r<r li 4 /irn nr.\\ 4 A \\\\7 n C li _\nington to live with him. As yet\nhe has made no arrangements for\nsecuring a winter home there,\nand made no statements regard\ning whether he would open up a\nhouse there when his family\ncame.\nSenator Clarke cannot tell\ndefinitely when he will leave tor\nWashington. He will not take\nany members of his family along\nwith him to the national capital.\nBoth were noncommittal as to\nwhether or not they would bring\nup anything before the senate\nthat would be of unusual benefit\nor interest to Arkansas.\nECHOS FROM DANIELL CASE.\nWoman Over Whom the Magness Kill\ning Occurred Now Seeks Divorce.\nFrom Kansas City Times.\nBecause she alleges her hus\nband, Eugene F. Daniell, was\nconvicted of a felony in Arkansas\nand sent to the penitentiary,\nTheresa E. Daniell, a trained\nnurse, brought suit for divorce\nyesterday. They were married\nAugust 19, 1904, and lived to\ngether less than two years.\nEugene F. Daniell, known in\nMena as Harry Daniell, killed Dr.\nW. L. Magness August 19, 1904.\nThe date of the marriage as\ngiven above is incorrect. It was\nprobably the year previous that\nthey were married.\nDaniell was given a two-year\nsentence and was paidcncd after\nserving a portion of the term.\nReports of improper relations\nexisting between the well known\nphysician and Mrs. Daniell led\nup to the killing and caused a\ndecided sensation, coning, as it\ndid, while the city was in the\nmidst of its annual lair and cele\nbration in 1904.\nHolding the Balloon Trophy.\nBerlin, Nov. 23.\u2014A dispatch to the\nI.okal Anzelger from Bremen declares\niunt me tuoiumo ttuiuunurs uirrr urt'\nhdloing the cup awarded to Herr\nErbsloeh, the German aeronaut, for\nwinning the recent international bal\nloon race at St. Louis, for the payment\nof duty as silver. Herr Erbsloeh has\nprotested declining to pay the levy\nuntil the central authorities have de\ncided whether the cup shall enter free\nas an object of art or Is really dutia\nble as silver.\nHer Bravery Recognized.\nNewport, Nov. 23.\u2014Mrs. Ida Lewis\nWilson, or Ida Lewis, as she Is more\npopularly known, keeper of the Lime\nRock Light house, at the southern end\nof Newport harbor has been again\nhonored for bravery in saving lives in\nher term at that point. Andrew Car\nnegie has put her on his private list,\ninsuring $30 a month during her life\ntime.\nProceeding* Against Pittsburg, Kan.\nTopeka, Kan., Nov. 20.\u2014Attorneys\nrepresenting the city of Pittsburr,\nKan., came before Attorney General\nJackson Monday and entered Into a\nstipulation with the state by which\nthe state will in ten days file Its for\nmal accusation against the city of\nPittsburg and the city will have 2d\ndays to answer. The accusations are\na preliminary to proceedings against\nthe officers for contempt In not en\nf -cing the prohibition\nWellman Reaches New York.\nNew York, Nov. 23.\u2014Walter Well\nman, leader of the Chicago Record\nHerald Polar expedition, who is re\nturning from his first attempt to\nreach the North Pole by balloon, ar\nrived in New York Thursday from\nCherbourg on the steamer Majestic.\nHe will visit his fami.y in Philadelphia\nand then go to Chicago.\nTHERE IS NO REASON\nwhy your baby should he thill, and fretful\nduring the night. Worms are the cause ol\nthin, sickly babies. It Is natural that a heal\nthy baby should be fat and sleep well. II\nyour baby doesn\u2019t retain Its food, don't ex per\ntinent with colic cures and other medicine,\nbut try a bottle of White\u2019s Cream Vermifuge\nand see your baby have color and laugh ai\nIt should. Sold by Jackson Drug Co.\nf\u00abK I ill\n_\nSenator Hasnlrough, of North Da\nkota, Would Put Institution\nin Chicago or St Louis.\nWEST WOULD BE GREATLY BENEFITTED\nThe Senator Says, However, That ths\nPresident\u2019s Recommendations Should\nFirst be Enacted Into Law\u2014Will In\ntroduce the Bill at Proper Time\u2014\nBlames Eastern Banks.\nWashington, Nov. 23.\u2014A federal\ncentral bank of Issue, located either\nin fit. Louis or Chicago, is advocated\nby Senator Hansbrough of South Da\nkota, a member of the senate com\nmittee on finance and the first mem\nber of that important committee to\nvoice his opinions In relation to the\npresent financial situation and a pos\nsible legislative remedy.\nSenator Hansbrough, discussing\nthe subject of financial legislation,\nsaid:\n\u2018'Financial conditions in North Da\nkota are in good shape insofar as\ncrops, business, etc., are concerned,\nbut we have suffered severely from\nthe money stringency and the hoard\ning of money by eastern oanks.\n\u201cWill the coming congress enact fi\nnancial legislation promptly?\u201d was\nasked the senator.\n\u201cI hope so,\" was the reply. \u201cI un\nderstand that the president makes a\nclearcut and urgent recommendation\nIn his message for an emergency cur\nrency, a currency based on ample se\ncurity and so taxed that it will add\nelasticity to our circulating medium.\nI regard it as the duty of every re\nin Kr\u00bbE>\u00bb hmicou nf pnnPTPRi\nto respond promptly to the president\u2019s\nrecommendation. It should be rerneni\nbered that there Is no panic In the\nsense that there was one In 1893.\nThe times are good. It Is only money\nthat Is short and to some extent there\nIs a lack of confidence. That Is psy\nchological. The legislation recom\nmended by the president my not go\nfar enough, but it possesses intrinsic\nmerit in existing conditions and can\ndo no harm whatever.\n\u201cOf course I appreciate that the var\nious members of congress will have\nremedies which they consider more\nefficacious than simply the emergency\ncurrency plan, but I believe that they\nshould first respond to the president\u2019s\nrecommendation. If each member\nInsists on the scheme which most ap\npeals to him it will be months before\nanything can be accomplished. Rut\nwhen we have enacted legislation the\npresident recommends and by so do\ning have again put the wheels in mo\ntion, we can consider further meas\nures.\n\u201cAt the proper time I hope to In\ntroduce a bill providing for the estab\nlishment of a federal central bank of\nIssue, to be located at Chicago or St.\nLouis, and to be under the immediate\ncontrol of the secretary of the treas\nury. That is what is needed, and it\nis my ooservation tnat me more tne\npeople study the defects of our flnan\nj clal system the more they appreciate\nthe necessity of such an institution.\nI would authorize this bank to make\nloans, to Incorporated banks only, on\nstate, county and municipal bonds and\nother gilt-edged securities.\n\u201cIt might be well to authorize this\nbank to issue currency secured by\nUnited States bonds; or, being in fact\na government institution, its circula\ntion could well stand upon its reserve\nfund, and If need be on its general\nassets. In .times of currency scarcity\nthe bank could issue increased\namounts and distribute it to points\nwhere It was most needed, while the\nissue and withdrawal of this currency\nwould be controlled by the secretary\nof the treasury.\n\"Such a bank, had it existed during\nthe present stringency, would have\nIssued currency and sent It to the\nnorthwest to move the crops. With\nthese arriving at the seaboard, Euro\npean money would have flowed In to\nrelieve the scarcity In the east, and\nthe shortage would have passed with\nout causing the grave Inconvenience\nit has occasioned. Being located\nIn the middle west, the directors of\nthe federal central bank would keep\nIn close touch with the conditions and\nresources in that section, where the\nvast exportable wealth of the country\nIs produced. They could forsee emer\ngencies which are apt to occur when\nwe have large or high-priced crops to\nmove and could keep sufficiently close\nto unusual situations to deal with\nthem effectively.\u201d\nA New Jersey Egg Famine.\nJersey City, N. J.. Nov. 22.\u2014Selected\nstrictly fresh eggs sold in Jersey\nCity Wednesday at 75 cents a dozer..\nThis Is said to be the highest pric^\npaid for 32 years. The best grades of\neggs sold on Monday at 60 centB a\ndozen. Other grades sold at 38 to 48\ncents.\nTrans-Mississippi Commercial Con\ngress Chooses J. R. Case, of Ab\nilene, as President.\n\nMEETS IN SAN FRANCISCO NEXT YEAR\nAction of President Roosevelt and\nSecretary Cortelyou In Issuing Bond\nand Certificates to Relieve Financial\nStringency Indorsed After a Warm\nDebate.\nMuskogee. Ok., Nov. 23.\u2014San Fran\ncisco Thursday afternoon was select\ned as the city in which the Trans\nMississippi Commercial congress will\nmeet next year.\nThe following officers were elected:\nPresident, J. II. Case, Abilene, Kan.;\nfirst vice president, I. T. Pryor, San\nAntonio, Texas; second vice president,\nM. O. Lawrence, North Dakota; third\nvice president, W. F. Baker, Council\nBluffs, Iowa; fourth vice president, C.\nD. Galbreath, Denver; secretary, A.\nFrancis, Cripple Creel. Col.\nRobert Owen and Thomas P. Gore.\nUnited Senators elect, met in a de\nbate during the session and the\npowers of both were put to the test.\nThe committee on resolutions had\nrejected the resolution commending\nthe action of President Roosevelt and\nSecretary Cortelyou in issuing gov\nernment certificates of Indebtedness\nto relieve the financial stringency and\nurging citizens to invest In the certifi\ncates, offered Wednesday David R.\nFrancis, ex-governor of Missouri, by a\nvote or YL to 11, me uuauuiou\nIn* the deciding vote. Because the\ncommittee was so evenly divided the\nresolution was referred back to the\nhouse. The sentiment seemed to\nfavor the action of the committee.\nSenator Gore urged that the house\nvote the resolution down. Senator\nOwen followed his colleague, declar\ning that the resolution should be car\nried. The house went to the side of\nthe Indian senator and when the vote\nwas called the resolution was adopted\nby a vote of 196 to 43.\nSenator Owen scored Moty Tiger,\nchief of the Creek nation, for \"allow\ning the federal government to place\nwords in his mouth through the'in\nstrument of an interpreter.\u201d Chief\nTiger bitterly assaflefl Senator Owen\nWednesday In a speech before the\ncongress.\nIn speaking of the nation's Insular\npossession. Senator William J. Stone,\nof Missouri, declared that if the\nUnited States intended to hold the\nPhilippine Islands they should be\ngiven self-government Immediately.\nHe believed, be said, that a satisfac\ntory tseaty could be made between\nthis nation and the nations of the\nworld regarding the future indepen\ndent government of the Philippines.\nA resolution was presented by the\nretailers of the Trans-MIsslssippl coun\ntry asking that the congress declare\nagainst the parcels post.\nWhen the cities were lighting for\nthe honor of the next annual meet\ning of the congress, President Love\nland, In a voice choked with sobg\ntold of his sitting with the committee\nof 50 appointed to receive the mes\nsages of sympathy which flashed from\nthe corners of the earth Into the\nstricken city of San Francisco on the\ndays that followed the great horror\nand with tears in his eyes he asked\nthat the honor be given to the metro\npolis of the West. San Francisco had\nwon before the cheers that answered\nPresident Loveland's speech had died\nfrom the hall.\nA Hethodist Minister Reccr mends\nChamberlain\u2019s Cough Remedy\nWe have used Chamberlain s Cough Kem\nedy In our home for seven years, and It has\nalways proved to be reliable. We have\nfound that It would do more than the manu\nfacturers claim of it. It Is especially giol\nfor whooping cough.\nREV. JAMES A. Ll.WIS\nPastor Mllaca, Minn., M. K. Church.\nChamberlain's Cough Ilemedy Is sold by\nJackson Drug Co., and All Dealers.\nMoney to Loan.\nI have some money I hold in\ntrust that I can loan you at regu\nlar rates of interest, on mort\ngage or collateral security. Ad\ndress Henry Lightcap, Eaglelon,\nArk. 46w4\nFarm for rent for cash or grain\nrent\u2014On the road from Rocky to\nPotter. Plenty of fruit and good\ncott n In d on the farm. For\nparticulars inquire of Mary Bales.\nRocky. Polk county, Ark.\n43 2m* J, F. Everett, Lacy, la.\nOats, Fodder and Hay Wanted.\nAnyone having sheaf oats,\npood fodder or hay for sale please\nI call at Star office soot\nrvTTVVYWW\n*8\u00bb\nGirlhood and Scoffs Emulsion are\nlinked together.\nThe girl who takes Scoffs Emul- A\nsion has plenty of rich, red blood; she is\nplump, active and energetic.\nThe reason is that at a psriod when a girl\u2019s S\ndigestion is weak, Scoffs Emulsion\nprovides her with powerful nourishment in A\neasily digested form.\nI\nI\nAn Old Carpet.\nJust to enliven up things a little we will sell any of our\n$2.50 Rugs for $1.50.\nOur $3.50 Hugs for $2.50.\nThese are all new and up-to-date patterns and as this\nis the season of the year when Rugs are needed the\nmost, you will do well to take advantage of this sale.\nThese Prices Are for Cash Only.\nB.F. ADKISSON.PROP.\nI\nBUGGIES!!\nA Carload of Them\nThis shipment is composed of the well known\nAnchor and John Deere Makes\nand consists of substantial and well made\nVehicles at $50 up to the finest at $135. Come\nand take a look anyhow.\nThe Nights Are Getting Frosty\nSo don\u2019t fail to look over your Heating Stoves.\nWe can sell you the best Heaters\u2014fuel savers,\ntoo, at low prices. You will be more comfort\nable with one of our Heaters in your houre.\nW. E. WATKINS BRO.\nPickering Avenue, Mena, Arkansas.\nII SM\nI _\"\nWhen You Take\nMedicine\nPrescribed by a physician half the time\nyou don't know its ingredients. So you\nmust place implicit confidence in your\ndoctor and your druggist. It will not\nbe misplaced as far as prescription fill\ning is concerned if you lodee your\nprescriptions with us. We guarantee\nthat they will be filled as directed. We\nask your patronage and ask you to in\nspect our store and labratory.\nThe Mena Pharmacy tffggg\nrsnTwnOD\nGeneral Merchandise.\nCustomers don\u2019t expect to find the largest\nstock in my store, but soon learn that I care\nfully study their needs and buv what they\nwant\u2014goods of reliable sort. Besides that,\nmy expenses are light, which enables me to\nsell goods at a smaller margin than some of\nthe more expensively conducted stores.\nI Ask a Fair Trial SouMenaenArktreet\n1_/\nWE WILL SELL\nyou an\nEdison Phonograph\nor a\nVictor Talking Machine\non the installment plan.\nDonaldson\u2019s Bookstore\nPhone 182.\naaz.tiy j, .P wwjjuw marnmn\n\nFurniture and Hardware\nChinaware and Crockery.\nI have built up my business by honest deal\ning and will hold it by the same method.\n3' -A. EICHAEDS\nDe Queen Street, New Brick Opposite His Old Stand.\nFOk prices on car lots on\nAlfalfa'S,\u2019 Hay\nWIRE OR WRITS\nthe Kansas city hay co\nKANSAS CITY, MO.\n..j\n--_j\nELMER J. LUNDY j\nattorn ky-at-law\nPAVISBLDO. MKNA, ARK. I\nJ\n11. <3. Shaver, Sr. W. Minor llphlu\nSHAVER PIPKIN\nLAWYERS\nOffice at Court Houae, Mena, Ark.\nWill practice In all the court* of the\nstate.\nLand, probate collections. \u00abPV*.\nLand titles Investigated and cloud* re\nmoved. _n.\u00bb\nAbstract a furnished. taxt\u00bb P\u00ae*d\nforfeiture* contested.\nEstute* of decedent* and\nvtstigated, settlement* of ad minis' _\nto?h and guardbin* overhauled. Lor\nk>X>ond\u00abnce solicited.\nMena Evening Star, Month 40c.","height":"29868","width":"20940"}}
